<P><B>Context: OMB's Role</B><BR>

<P><B>OMB's predominant mission is to assist the President in overseeing the preparation of the Federal<BR>
budget and to supervise its administration in Executive Branch agencies. In helping to formulate the<BR>
President's spending plans, OMB evaluates the effectiveness of agency programs, policies, and<BR>
procedures, assesses competing funding demands among agencies, and sets funding priorities. OMB<BR>
ensures that agency reports, rules, testimony, and proposed legislation are consistent with the<BR>
President's budget and with Administration policies. </B><BR>

<P><B>In addition, OMB oversees and coordinates the Administration's procurement, financial<BR>
management, information, and regulatory policies. In each of these areas, OMB's role is to help<BR>
improve administrative management, to develop better performance measures and coordinating<BR>
mechanisms, and to reduce any unnecessary burdens on the public.</B><BR>

