<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>	Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part I</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P>
<P><B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Document Name<B>:	</B><B>Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part I</B><BR>
Date:	<B>		</B><B>02/13/95</B><BR>
Owner:	<B>		</B><B>National Performance Review and OMB</B>		<BR>

<B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Title: Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part I<BR>

<P>Date: February 13, 1995 <BR>

<P>Author: National Performance Review and OMB<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>*****************************************************************<BR>

<P>                            PRIVATIZATION <BR>

<P>                            RESOURCE GUIDE <BR>

<P>                                  and <BR>

<P>                             STATUS REPORT<BR>

<P>*****************************************************************<BR>

<P>February 13, 1995<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>FOREWORD<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>     This document is a compilation of selected information about <BR>

<P>privatization concepts and activities--who is doing them, what documents <BR>

<P>might be of interest, implementation strategies and constraints, and <BR>

<P>potential contacts--for the benefit of agencies who are not familiar <BR>

<P>with the subject and do not know where to look.  It is not exhaustive.    <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     In addition to the information provided herein, there are two <BR>

<P>forthcoming activities which may be of interest to those engaged in an <BR>

<P>assessment of privatization alternatives:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     A half day workshop, sponsored by the National Performance Review, <BR>

<P>is tentatively scheduled for February 28, 1995 at the Office of Thrift <BR>

<P>Supervision auditorium, 1700 G Street, N.W., Washington, D.C.  Agency <BR>

<P>NPR Liaisons will be apprised when this event becomes firm.  Topics by <BR>

<P>federal officials include:<BR>

<P>     <BR>

<P>-     Asset Transfer and Leasing<BR>

<P>-     Outsourcing and Competition<BR>

<P>-     Employee Empowerment Through Ownership    <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     A two-day conference, sponsored by the National Council on Public-<BR>

<P>Private Partnership, will be held March 30-31, 1995 at the J.W. Marriott <BR>

<P>Hotel, 1331 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Washington, D.C.  The NPR has <BR>

<P>been active in attempting to focus the agenda and obtain the best <BR>

<P>federal speakers possible; private sector speakers will also <BR>

<P>participate.  Notices will be distributed by mid-February.  Topics <BR>

<P>include:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-     Administration and Congressional Views<BR>

<P>-     Organizational Restructuring<BR>

<P>-     Direct Privatization<BR>

<P>-     Competition<BR>

<P>-     The Role of Labor<BR>

<P>-     Government Corporations and Spin-offs<BR>

<P>-     Implementing and Financing Federal Privatization Programs<BR>

<P>-     Employee Empowerment Through Ownership<BR>

<P>-     State and Local Devolution<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>CONTENTS<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>FOREWORD<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>1      INTRODUCTION<BR>

<P>2      FRANCHISING<BR>

<P>3      PRIVATIZATION<BR>

<P>          Background<BR>

<P>          Executive Order 12893, Principles for Infrastructure <BR>

<P>          Investment<BR>

<P>          Executive Order 12803, Infrastructure Privatization<BR>

<P>          Additional Privatization Initiatives<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>4      EMPLOYEE STOCK OWNERSHIP PROGRAMS (ESOPs) <BR>

<P>          How They Operate<BR>

<P>          Selecting Activities for FED CO-OP<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>5      OTHER FACTORS TO CONSIDER<BR>

<P>          Conflict of Interest and Federal Ethics Limitations<BR>

<P>          Over-Reaction to Procurement Problems<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>    APPENDICES <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     A     .Privatization Initiatives in the FY 1996 Budget    <BR>

<P>     B     .&quot;GOGO TO GOCO--On The Road To Privatization,&quot; <BR>

<P>              National Institute for Petroleum and Energy Research, <BR>

<P>              Bartlesville, Oklahoma (Case Study)  .<BR>

<P>     C     .Selected Contacts <BR>

<P>     D     .Selected Bibliography   <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>INTRODUCTION<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>     On December 19, 1994, President Clinton formally initiated Phase II <BR>

<P>of the work of the National Performance Review (NPR).  From its <BR>

<P>inception in early 1993, the work of the NPR focused on four powerful <BR>

<P>themes:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Putting Customers First,<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Cutting Red Tape, <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Empowering Employees To Get Results, and <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Cutting Back to Basics.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The results of the first year's efforts dealt primarily with the <BR>

<P>first three themes.  As a consequence, Cutting Back to Basics became an <BR>

<P>important focus for Phase II.  Cutting Back to Basics means taking a <BR>

<P>hard look at the things which government does and determining what <BR>

<P>changes to make in federal programs and functions, if any.  It also <BR>

<P>means moving the service delivery capability to the most effective <BR>

<P>provider and putting incentives into place to bring about the desired <BR>

<P>results.  In general, a refocusing and downsizing of federal activities <BR>

<P>will result.    <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     There are five basic ways of downsizing the federal government.  <BR>

<P>From the broadest to narrowest perspective, they include;<BR>

<P>     <BR>

<P>1     .Service Termination.  This approach reflects a government review <BR>

<P>of the existing commercial, State or local government service market and <BR>

<P>a decision that a service need not be provided by the federal <BR>

<P>government.  This option includes many federalism concepts.  Electrical <BR>

<P>power generation and distribution (rural electrification), and helium <BR>

<P>production and sales are also examples of services that fit into this <BR>

<P>category.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>2     .Privatization.  Privatization implies that the government is <BR>

<P>currently providing the service, but no longer sees the need to be in <BR>

<P>direct control of its provision, operations or maintenance.  <BR>

<P>Privatization reflects the sale of assets and related service <BR>

<P>requirements (rights) by the government.  However, it also includes <BR>

<P>assumptions that services are necessary and must be provided in the <BR>

<P>future.  It is rarely simple divestiture, as outlined above.  The sale <BR>

<P>agreements themselves establish and refer to the regulatory and <BR>

<P>oversight environment that will continue to exist to assure that public <BR>

<P>and/or agency access and service requirements are maintained.  This may <BR>

<P>or may not include agreed-upon user fees or rate commission (utility) <BR>

<P>oversight.  Privatization can include sale to or forgiveness of debt <BR>

<P>from other public authorities or to private sector investors.   Simple <BR>

<P>examples include waste water treatment plants, airports, ports, bridges, <BR>

<P>parks, and recreation facilities.  Government exerts control through <BR>

<P>regulatory and sale covenants.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>3     .Quasi-Government Corporations.  This approach recognizes that <BR>

<P>there is a definite public need for a service at the federal level.  <BR>

<P>Generally it is a service that can readily be provided by the private <BR>

<P>sector, but there is no commercial service market able or willing to <BR>

<P>take on the responsibility.  In effect, instead of providing the service <BR>

<P>directly as a public (in-house) good, the government opts to create a <BR>

<P>corporation and a market where there is none today.  Fannie Mae, Connie <BR>

<P>Mack, etc. are examples.  Another example is Conrail, where there was a <BR>

<P>public need and no private sector interest in providing the financial or <BR>

<P>operating assets necessary--the risks were simply too high relative to <BR>

<P>expected returns.  Amtrak is currently considered a part of this <BR>

<P>category.  Government exerts control through a combination of limited <BR>

<P>operational and management controls, (board member, owner of <BR>

<P>preferential stock, budget review authority, appropriations, etc.) and <BR>

<P>regulatory controls.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>4     .Creation of Public/Private Partnerships.  This approach reflects <BR>

<P>a joint public and private sector investment relationship.  The <BR>

<P>government may share in the ownership of assets and may share in <BR>

<P>operational responsibilities.   Many hub airports facilities and <BR>

<P>regional transportation Authorities (e.g., the Port Authority of New <BR>

<P>York) fall into this category.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     5     .Competition.  This is the &quot;outsourcing&quot; or &quot;contracting out&quot; <BR>

<P>alternative (FAR recompetitions and OMB Circular A-76 make/buy <BR>

<P>decisions).  It reflects a decision by the government to remain fully <BR>

<P>responsible for the provision of all services and management decisions.  <BR>

<P>The question is whether the service can be more effectively procured <BR>

<P>through in-house or contract sources.  Management efforts to improve in-<BR>

<P>house productivity, accountability, increase the incentives to be cost <BR>

<P>effective and customer oriented and to better define work are severely <BR>

<P>limited without competition.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     How do you sort through programs and functions to make these <BR>

<P>considerations?  To begin with, at a meeting on January 12, 1995 with <BR>

<P>agency representatives, the Vice President asked the agencies to develop <BR>

<P>a decision process similar to that shown in Exhibit 1.  As a first step, <BR>

<P>agencies must first determine whether the program or function is <BR>

<P>critical to the agencies mission based upon &quot;customer input.&quot;  The <BR>

<P>criticality of &quot;customer input&quot; can be seen as agencies think through <BR>

<P>the rest of the process and are confronted by decisions which require <BR>

<P>prioritization and insight as to how well the activities are performed.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Divesting of those activities that are no longer an appropriate <BR>

<P>agency line of business may not be easy, and the options shown in Figure <BR>

<P>1 of &quot;terminate&quot; or &quot;privatize&quot; require a separate analysis as to timing <BR>

<P>and appropriateness of the mechanism(s) to be employed.      <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The second decision point shown in Exhibit 1 is that of devolution <BR>

<P>to the state or local level, which may also involve some joint <BR>

<P>partnership on a short-term or continuing basis.  Again, aspects of <BR>

<P>&quot;privatization&quot; emerge.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     At the third level of decision, the question of cutting costs and <BR>

<P>improving performance through the injection of competition.  Discussion <BR>

<P>of the options for franchising and privatization are provided in the <BR>

<P>sections which follow.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Five agencies have already analyzed their activities along similar <BR>

<P>lines.  These include the Department of Housing and Urban Development <BR>

<P>(HUD), GSA, the Department of Energy, the Office of Personnel <BR>

<P>Management, and DOT.  The results of their efforts and the mechanisms <BR>

<P>employed are summarized in Exhibit 2.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>**********************************************************************<BR>

<P>EXHIBIT 2.  SUMMARY OF MECHANISMS USED BY FIVE AGENCIES<BR>

<P>TO SAVE $20 BILLION<BR>

<P>**********************************************************************<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Consolidation<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>HUD is consolidating 60 grant programs into 3 performance grants:  <BR>

<P>Housing Certificates, Affordable Housing Fund, and Community Opportunity <BR>

<P>Fund.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>DOT will consolidate its 10 agencies into 3 around the themes of either <BR>

<P>(a) land, sea, or air, or (b) infrastructure, safety, and Coast Guard.<BR>

<P>DOT will consolidate its 30 grant programs into 3:  a unified grant to <BR>

<P>states and cities, new state infrastructure banks, and discretionary <BR>

<P>grants.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Vouchers<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>HUD is shifting funding from 3,400 public housing authorities to tenants <BR>

<P>who can then determine where to purchase support (similar to G.I. Bill).<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Devolution<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>DOT will give states more power over transportation-related spending as <BR>

<P>part of $6.7 billion package.<BR>

<P>GSA will delegate additional responsibility to federal agencies <BR>

<P>regarding their performance of administrative and support activities.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Program Cancellation<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>DOE will shave $1.2 billion over five years from its applied research <BR>

<P>programs, including the Clean Coal Technology Program, and close at <BR>

<P>least one laboratory facility.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Administrative Changes<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>HUD will save $800 million through administrative changes, attrition, <BR>

<P>and buyouts over five years.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>DOE will make unspecified cuts in the management and operations of its <BR>

<P>nuclear and chemical waste clean up program to save $4.4 billion.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>OPM will eliminate 1,800 more positions over the next five years.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Privatization<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>DOE will sell the Naval Petroleum Reserves at Elk Hills and Teapot Dome <BR>

<P>to private industry and save $1.6 billion.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>******************<BR>

<P>Other Divesting<BR>

<P>******************<BR>

<P>HUD will establish the Federal Housing Administration as a government-<BR>

<P>owned corporation.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>DOT will move air traffic control operations and its 40,000 employees to <BR>

<P>a semi-public corporation as part of $6.7 billion package.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>GSA will review each of its operational business lines to determine <BR>

<P>which should be transferred to the agencies or privatized.  GSA will <BR>

<P>also consider the use of Employee Stock Ownership Plans (ESOPs).  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>DOE will sell uranium no longer needed for national defense purposes <BR>

<P>after rendering it suitable for commercial power reactors.<BR>

<P>**********************************************************************<BR>

<P>**********************************************************************<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>FRANCHISING<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>     For purposes of this discussion, &quot;franchising&quot; is an <BR>

<P>entrepreneurial activity within a government organization which provides <BR>

<P>common administrative support services to other federal agencies or <BR>

<P>other components within the same federal agency.      <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The establishment of a Franchise Fund Pilot Program was authorized <BR>

<P>by the Government Management Reform Act of 1994 (GMRA) to give federal <BR>

<P>managers improved management tools and incentives to operate more cost-<BR>

<P>effectively.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The federal government has employed a variety of funding mechanisms <BR>

<P>in the past for common administrative services under such titles as <BR>

<P>working capital funds, revolving funds, industrial funds, and supply and <BR>

<P>service funds, and there was wide variety in their methods operation.  <BR>

<P>Currently, agencies are providing construction management, financial, <BR>

<P>security, purchasing, warehousing, transportation, education and <BR>

<P>numerous other services, as well as, products to federal agencies which <BR>

<P>are inside and outside their own departments.  Significant savings may <BR>

<P>be available to agencies as sellers and purchases of services from <BR>

<P>federal franchises.<BR>

<P>
<P>
