<TITLE>	Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part II</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P>
<P><B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Document Name<B>:	</B><B>Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part II</B><BR>
Date:	<B>		</B><B>02/13/95</B><BR>
Owner:	<B>		</B><B>National Performance Review and OMB</B>		<BR>

<B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Title: Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part II<BR>

<P>Date: February 13, 1995<BR>

<P>Author: National Performance Review and OMB<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Despite the very positive aspects offered by many of these prior <BR>

<P>arrangements, there were enough improprieties historically, that cause <BR>

<P>for concern about their operation was often justified.  The Franchise <BR>

<P>Fund concept, on the other hand, can be thought of as an approach which <BR>

<P>incorporates the best of these earlier mechanisms and avoids the worst.  <BR>

<P>In general, franchise funds incorporate at least three important <BR>

<P>characteristics; they are fully reimbursable, competitive, and meet <BR>

<P>standards.  Performance within a franchise may be accomplished with <BR>

<P>either in-house federal staff or by contractors.        <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Under the auspices of the federal Chief Financial Officers' Council <BR>

<P>(CFOC), a Franchise Fund Working Group has been laying the groundwork to <BR>

<P>implement the provisions of the GMRA, with the result that a Franchise <BR>

<P>Fund Pilot Program Application was forwarded to agency Chief Financial <BR>

<P>Officers and the Chairman of the Small Agency Council by OMB Director <BR>

<P>for Management John Koskinen on February 6, 1995.  An Applicants' <BR>

<P>Conference will be held on February 17, 1995 to review the scope and <BR>

<P>benefits of the program, and to provide information on how to complete <BR>

<P>the Application.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Awards to the pilot programs are scheduled for May 1995.  A <BR>

<P>Directory of the more than 150 organizations currently offering one or <BR>

<P>more common administrative services will be available for the February <BR>

<P>17th Conference.  (Copies of the Directory after February 17th can be <BR>

<P>obtained from Phil LaBonte, GSA, 202-273-4665.)  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     A two-day conference is now in the planning stages for June 1995 <BR>

<P>which will focus on how to establish and operate a franchise fund and <BR>

<P>guide is now being developed to help agencies in their implementation <BR>

<P>efforts.  The conference is being planned jointly by the CFOC Franchise <BR>

<P>Fund Working Group and Association for Public Policy Analysis and <BR>

<P>Management. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     A final word on franchising.  The benefits cited most often with <BR>

<P>regard to &quot;franchise&quot; type activities tie to the funding and service <BR>

<P>flexibilities the approach provides to agencies.  Many overlook the <BR>

<P>sense of &quot;order&quot; it brings to employees who want to do a good job and <BR>

<P>are constantly frustrated by the demands on their time.  Customer <BR>

<P>service standards are usually not well-defined and the expectations of <BR>

<P>both the employee and the customer remain unmet.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     By entering into a fee-for-service environment, employees find that <BR>

<P>economics become the great leveler.  Fee schedules are tied to work <BR>

<P>products; economics helps customers and employees adjust their <BR>

<P>priorities and predefine expectations.  Employees of the Defense <BR>

<P>Logistics Agency, for example, found that when they moved into a fee-<BR>

<P>for-service environment, they are able to provide quality service at a <BR>

<P>much lower cost.  Their time is more productive--job satisfaction <BR>

<P>improved.  Everyone wins! <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     It is further worth noting before we move on to the section on <BR>

<P>Privatization, that Franchising is a step in that direction.  In some <BR>

<P>cases, the organizational dynamics may be such that it is the first step <BR>

<P>in a sequence of actions which ultimately move the entity into one of <BR>

<P>the privatization options discussed in the next section.            <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>PRIVATIZATION<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>BACKGROUND<BR>

<P>
<P>     This Resource Guide and Status Report is designed to provide <BR>

<P>federal managers with a starting point in their consideration of <BR>

<P>privatization as an option for Phase II reinvention.  The Resource Guide <BR>

<P>and Status Report is not an exhaustive review of privatization, but <BR>

<P>rather is a glimpse at what is becoming an increasingly important and <BR>

<P>dynamic public management tool.  Privatization seeks to optimize the in-<BR>

<P>house and contract workload mix and, thereby, achieve cost-effective <BR>

<P>federal services.  Privatization is defined as one of the following:  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>(1) the private development and operation of public-use infrastructure <BR>

<P>and the provision of public services that have traditionally been <BR>

<P>provided by the state; (2) contracting out of services, which does not <BR>

<P>usually include private sharing of financial responsibility; (3) the <BR>

<P>sale of state-owned enterprises to private firms, with the expectation <BR>

<P>that the buyer will improve operating efficiency, invest new capital, <BR>

<P>and take full advantage of the enterprises's commercial development <BR>

<P>potential, all at lower cost to the state.&quot;  (Source:  Gregory Fishbein, <BR>

<P>202-331-3623, Price-Waterhouse Transportation and Utility Finance <BR>

<P>Group.)  <BR>

<P>
<P>     While the concept of privatization of federal services is not new, <BR>

<P>it is experiencing a period of heightened awareness. Government services <BR>

<P>have been contracted-out (sometimes referred to as &quot;outsourcing,&quot; to <BR>

<P>private providers almost since the start of the Republic.  In addition, <BR>

<P>concessions to conduct business with the public have been granted in <BR>

<P>numerous situations where it was to the advantage of the government to <BR>

<P>have the service provided by the private sector.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The public most often hears about federal privatization efforts in <BR>

<P>the form of &quot;government corporations,&quot; of which some 22 have been <BR>

<P>established under the Government Corporation Control Act of 1945.  (For <BR>

<P>more information on this, see the article entitled &quot;Government Inc.,&quot; in <BR>

<P>the February 1995 issue of Government Executive.  It is also worth <BR>

<P>noting that Susan Lee of the Department of Transportation prepared &quot;A <BR>

<P>Study of Government Corporations&quot;which addresses the role of government, <BR>

<P>how government corporations differ from a revolving fund, and <BR>

<P>considerations for auditing, budgeting, procurement, and personnel.)<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Setting up a government corporation, however, is only one of <BR>

<P>several privatization-like approaches which can be taken.  In fact, some <BR>

<P>have said that &quot;delegating a governmental function to a government <BR>

<P>corporation is not the same thing as privatizing it.&quot;  The point to be <BR>

<P>made here is that the focus of NPR Phase II is to enable the government <BR>

<P>to more effectively focus on those things which it should and can do, <BR>

<P>and to put incentives in place to cause these things to perform <BR>

<P>optimally.  New and different types of partnerships continue to emerge <BR>

<P>to meet this challenge, including some that are not easily categorized. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Increasingly, major federal programs have been operated by the <BR>

<P>private sector.  In the 1980's and early 1990's, the Department of <BR>

<P>Defense (DOD) contracted for more than 12,000 units of leased military <BR>

<P>family housing for its personnel.  GSA leases over 150 million square <BR>

<P>feet of private full-service office space for government agencies.  <BR>

<P>Contractors fight forest fires on government land, while private day <BR>

<P>care providers tend to the children of federal employees at numerous <BR>

<P>locations, including the CIA. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Training aircraft at several military bases are maintained by <BR>

<P>contractor personnel, while the Marine Corps' Maritime Prepositioning <BR>

<P>Ships are owned and crewed by civilian companies. Cafeterias and mess <BR>

<P>halls have been privatized to feed civilian and military personnel <BR>

<P>better, faster, and cheaper than had their government predecessors.  <BR>

<P>Federal property is used by banks, credit unions, retail stores, and <BR>

<P>fast-food restaurants which cater to the needs of federal employees and <BR>

<P>the public.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Local and state governments have been deeply involved in <BR>

<P>privatization and have a wealth of experience that should be reviewed <BR>

<P>when considering this approach.  The list of local initiatives is long <BR>

<P>and growing constantly.  Services such as health care, school bus <BR>

<P>maintenance, prisons, warehousing, road maintenance, water treatment, <BR>

<P>fire services, ambulance/emergency medical care, computer <BR>

<P>operation/maintenance, elementary education, golf course operation, and <BR>

<P>food service, are just a few of the services that have been successfully <BR>

<P>transferred to the private sector. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     In the past two decades privatization has also taken hold in many <BR>

<P>foreign countries.  The British rail system has been privatized, along <BR>

<P>with water and telecommunications providers. In New Zealand, public <BR>

<P>sector employment has been cut in half as state owned enterprises have <BR>
been sold.  Argentina has sold its rail system, power plants, airports, <BR>

<P>telecommunications satellite network, toll road concessions, and <BR>

<P>water/sewer service systems to the private sector.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     In country after country governments have turned to the private <BR>

<P>sector to improve service and lower costs.  Many of the companies that <BR>

<P>are now operating these privatized services are based in the United <BR>

<P>States and have invested billions of U.S. dollars in these projects.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Section 5 (g) of the Federal Workforce Restructuring Act requires <BR>

<P>the President to take appropriate action to ensure that agencies do not <BR>

<P>convert the work of employees included in the 272,900 reduction target <BR>

<P>or the work of employees that accept a buyout to contract performance, <BR>

<P>unless a cost comparison demonstrates that there is a financial <BR>

<P>advantage to the government.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     In those cases where contracting out may be appropriate, agencies <BR>

<P>have been advised by Acting OMB Director Rivlin to comply with section <BR>

<P>5(g) of the Act through the conduct of OMB Circular A-76 comparisons, <BR>

<P>where applicable.  In those cases where Circular A-76 does not apply, <BR>

<P>such as Research and Development activities and activities that involve <BR>

<P>less than 10 Full-Time-Equivalents (FTEs), agencies may develop <BR>

<P>alternative cost comparison approaches that respond to the requirements <BR>

<P>of Section 5(g) or they may use Circular A-76 procedures.  We <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>believe that this guidance appropriately addresses the concern that <BR>

<P>agencies might otherwise be inclined to contract out activities to meet <BR>

<P>personnel ceilings, without a cost comparison to demonstrate a net <BR>

<P>benefit to the government.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Agencies that have pursued A-76 competitions, to both contract out <BR>

<P>performance and to contract in, indicate that it has been an effective <BR>

<P>mechanism for achieving savings without reducing the provision of needed <BR>

<P>services.  It has also been effective in ensuring that the determination <BR>

<P>of a financial advantage to the government is fair, open to all parties <BR>

<P>and based upon a level playing field.  Savings are achieved through <BR>

<P>efficiencies identified as a part of the competition process, both in-<BR>

<P>house and through contract bids, and through the implementation of <BR>

<P>improved contracting techniques.  Circular A-76 cost comparison and <BR>

<P>appeals procedures have ensured that all parties to the competitions <BR>

<P>have an equal access to the information and input to the decision <BR>

<P>process.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The NPR is not interested in promoting contracting out simply to <BR>

<P>make FTE reductions.  Section 5(g) and the requirements of Circular A-76 <BR>

<P>will ensure that conversions to or from contract are authorized only <BR>

<P>when shown to be cost-effective.  In its letter to agencies of August <BR>

<P>19, 1994, for example, OMB specifically requested that agencies maintain <BR>

<P>information on the status of their Section 5(g) contracting efforts, <BR>

<P>including information on the number of contracts awarded, FTE impacts <BR>

<P>and related dollar savings.  This same point was made in a February 4, <BR>

<P>1995, Washington Post article:  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>&quot;This is not a privatization exercise....This is a most cost-effective <BR>

<P>alternative exercise.  It would be irresponsible to do privatization for <BR>

<P>the sake of privatization.  Privatization itself is not the goal.  It's <BR>

<P>only a tool.&quot; <BR>

<P>                              Julia Stasch, GSA Deputy Administrator<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Our objective is to restore the public's faith in government by <BR>
managing our resources more effectively and by giving citizens and <BR>

<P>taxpayers more value for the dollar.  This requires that we look at the <BR>

<P>way work is performed and permit agencies the flexibility to manage <BR>

<P>their increasingly limited resources.   At the same time, we recognize <BR>

<P>our obligation to current employees, and to the taxpayer to minimize the <BR>

<P>adverse affect these changes could have on them.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     In almost every case where the operation of a federal agency is to <BR>

<P>be reviewed, privatization should be considered in whole or in part.  <BR>

<P>When making an initial decision concerning the retention of a federal <BR>

<P>program or function, the sample decision tree illustrated in Figure 1 <BR>

<P>should be helpful. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Federal privatization should not be viewed only with respect to the <BR>

<P>operations and maintenance of federal services.  Federal agencies are <BR>

<P>also influential in the opportunities to privatize at the state and <BR>

<P>local levels.  The privatization of federally-financed State and local <BR>

<P>infrastructure, for example, has been proposed as a means to leverage <BR>

<P>the equity in existing infrastructure for investment in new or expanded <BR>

<P>infrastructure. <BR>

<P>
<P>     The federal experience with privatization has shown that the <BR>

<P>private sector is often ready, willing and able to provide goods and <BR>

<P>services to federal customers that have reasonable goals, commercially <BR>

<P>acceptable risks, and an expectation of profitability.  The private for-<BR>

<P>profit sector, however, has neither the will nor the capability to <BR>

<P>undertake activities that do not meet these standards.  The private non-<BR>

<P>profit sector may fill some gaps, but usually will not take risks that <BR>

<P>will jeopardize the financial health of the institution.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Programs and functions (including services) which have little or no <BR>

<P>hope of being commercially viable should be eliminated or provided <BR>

<P>directly by federal resources.  In considering options to consolidate, <BR>

<P>terminate, franchise, incorporate, devolve, or outsource, agencies may <BR>

<P>want to seek answers to the following questions: <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Is the continued performance of the activity necessary to the <BR>

<P>mission of the agency?  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Would either service delivery, customer decisionmaking (vouchers), <BR>

<P>cost recognition, quality, or cost-effectiveness be enhanced through <BR>
franchising or privatization? <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Is the private sector physically, financially, and technologically <BR>

<P>capable of providing the program or function?  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Is there a legislative or regulatory prohibition or other barrier <BR>

<P>to private sector performance?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Can the requirement be defined with enough certainty to allow for <BR>

<P>competitive award of a contract for the program or function, and if not, <BR>

<P>why not?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Is there a consensus for the privatization of the project or <BR>

<P>function?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Is there sufficient time for procurement of the project or <BR>

<P>service?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     Can the human resource management needs be accommodated and dealt <BR>

<P>with fairly and expeditiously?  And, where applicable, has consideration <BR>

<P>been given to the provisions of FAR Section 52.207-3, Right of First <BR>

<P>Refusal? <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>EXECUTIVE ORDER 12893, PRINCIPLES FOR <BR>

<P>INFRASTRUCTURE INVESTMENT <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     This order, which was issued in January 1994, requires agencies to <BR>

<P>perform systematic analysis of benefits and costs of infrastructure <BR>

<P>programs.  The analysis should be quantitative and monetized to the <BR>

<P>maximum extent practicable, and it should consider a comprehensive set <BR>

<P>of policy options.  The order also is intended to promote efficient <BR>

<P>management through periodic reviews of operations and maintenance, <BR>

<P>pricing, demand management, and related strategies.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Private-sector participation is also encouraged, as agencies should <BR>

<P>work to reduce barriers to private provision of infrastructure.  <BR>

<P>Finally, agencies should encourage State and local recipients of federal <BR>

<P>grants to implement planning and information systems that support the <BR>

<P>above principles and enable the agencies to conduct system-level reviews <BR>

<P>of their programs.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Major programs (those with annual budgetary resources of $50 <BR>

<P>million or more) should be justified using the principles described <BR>

<P>above.  The order applies to direct spending and grant programs in the <BR>
following areas:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     transportation (Federal Highway Administration, Federal Railroad <BR>

<P>Administration, Federal Transit Administration, Federal Aviation <BR>

<P>Administration, and Coast Guard);<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     water resources (Army Corps of Engineers, Bureau of Reclamation, <BR>

<P>and Department of Agriculture);<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     environmental protection (EPA Clean Water State Revolving Funds <BR>

<P>and proposed Drinking Water State Revolving Funds, and USDA rural water <BR>

<P>and wastewater facilities grants and loans); and<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>o     energy (Power Marketing Administrations).<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>EXECUTIVE ORDER 12803, INFRASTRUCTURE <BR>

<P>PRIVATIZATION<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Executive Order 12803 was issued in April 1992, to encourage <BR>

<P>federal, State and local governments to leverage public and private <BR>

<P>sector investment in infrastructure and to use the equity in existing  <BR>

<P>infrastructure for new or expanded infrastructure.  Prior to E.O. 12803, <BR>

<P>the disposition of Federally-financed infrastructure was controlled by <BR>

<P>the &quot;Common Rule.&quot;  E.O. 12803 added to the &quot;Common Rule,&quot; as follows: <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>1     .States/locals could consider the sale/lease of assets that would <BR>

<P>continue to be used for original purposes. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>2     .Federal recoupment for the sale/lease of these assets may be <BR>

<P>calculated by multiplying the original contribution rate by the <BR>

<P>depreciated value.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>3     .State/local proceeds could be used for infrastructure, debt or <BR>

<P>tax relief.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The goal is to operate more efficiently and to provide better <BR>

<P>service at the lowest possible cost.  As suggested by Exhibit 3, <BR>

<P>privatization options can be thought of as a continuum; each option is <BR>

<P>effected by changes in personnel, asset ownership, cost, and other <BR>

<P>factors.  The selection of the appropriate option is difficult, and <BR>

<P>agencies should look to whether the option enables them to improve <BR>

<P>customer service (i.e., works better) and/or costs less.  Making this <BR>

<P>determination without customer input will be difficult.  
<P>

<P>
