<P>
<P><B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Document Name<B>:	</B><B>Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part IV</B><BR>
Date:	<B>		</B><B>02/13/95</B><BR>
Owner:	<B>		</B><B>National Performance Review and OMB</B>		<BR>

<B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Title: Privatization Resource Guide and Status Report Part IV<BR>

<P>Date: February 13, 1995<BR>

<P>Author: National Performance Review and OMB<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>OTHER FACTORS TO CONSIDER<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>CONFLICT OF INTEREST AND FEDERAL <BR>

<P>ETHICS LIMITATIONS<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Employee support and participation in the development of any <BR>

<P>privatization initiative is fundamental to the success of the process.  <BR>

<P>However, to ensure compliance with conflict-of-interest laws (18 USC 201 <BR>

<P>et. seq.) and ethics considerations and to protect employee interests, <BR>

<P>care must be taken to insulate employees from the government's decision <BR>

<P>process.  Care must also be taken to ensure that employees do not <BR>

<P>represent the interests of potential or current contractors, while still <BR>

<P>federal employees.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Any employee involved in the performance of the function under <BR>

<P>review and any employee that is directly involved in the development of <BR>

<P>the government's procurement documents is potentially at risk.  The risk <BR>

<P>is that their involvement could qualify them as &quot;procurement officials&quot; <BR>
and, therefore, not eligible for employment by the service contractor in <BR>

<P>a role which they helped create.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     For example, the Procurement Integrity Act and the Federal <BR>

<P>Acquisition Regulations define a procurement official as any civilian or <BR>

<P>military official or employee who has participated &quot;personally and <BR>

<P>substantially&quot; in any of the following activities:  drafting a <BR>

<P>specification or statement of work; review or approval of a <BR>

<P>specification or statement of work; preparation or development of a <BR>

<P>procurement or purchase request; preparation or issuance of a <BR>

<P>solicitation; evaluation of bids or proposals; source selection; <BR>

<P>contract negotiation or the review and approval of a contract award or <BR>

<P>modification.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     If the award is contingent upon a cost comparison conducted <BR>

<P>pursuant to Section 5(g) of the Federal Workforce Restructuring Act or <BR>

<P>OMB Circular A-76, employees who are substantially involved in the <BR>

<P>development and approval of the Management Plan, Most Efficient <BR>

<P>Organization and Government Bid may also be considered procurement <BR>

<P>officials.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The Procurement Integrity Act, 41 USC 423, governs the <BR>

<P>relationships between Government officials and current or potential <BR>
contractors.  The conflict of interest statutes, which include 18 USC <BR>

<P>210, 203, 205 and 208, generally prohibit any Federal employee from <BR>

<P>engaging in official activities that could conflict with personal <BR>

<P>interests.  The &quot;revolving door&quot; or post- employment restrictions at 18 <BR>

<P>USC 207 may also apply.  In some cases, Part 3.601 of the FAR may apply, <BR>

<P>which prohibits the award of a contract to a government employee or to a <BR>

<P>business concern or other organization owned or substantially owned or <BR>

<P>controlled by one or more government employees.  As noted in the FAR, <BR>

<P>however, this restriction is intended to avoid any conflict of interest <BR>

<P>that might arise between the employee's interests and the employee's <BR>

<P>continuing government duties.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     As privatization does not propose to award contracts to federal <BR>

<P>employees while still employed by the federal government, this is not <BR>

<P>seen as a major cause for concern.  Other restrictions, such as those of <BR>

<P>10 USC 2397 or Section 3.104 of the FAR, may apply to specific agency <BR>

<P>employees. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     As a practical matter, these restrictions do not materially affect <BR>

<P>most privatization initiatives or most of the employees involved, but <BR>
they could.  Employees should be consulted prior to making the actual <BR>

<P>decision to participate in a privatization initiative, but they must be <BR>

<P>protected from violating these conflict-of-interest laws.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Office of Government Ethics attorneys have stated that they &quot;do not <BR>

<P>believe that involvement in making an &quot;initial cut&quot; in potentially <BR>

<P>privatizable operations would create an actionable conflict of interest <BR>

<P>because the likelihood of financial gain would be too speculative.&quot;  The <BR>

<P>GSA General Counsel, Emily Hewitt, has assembled a file on these <BR>

<P>considerations.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The point of this discussion is that agencies should factor this <BR>

<P>consideration in their early planning to minimize the risk that it could <BR>

<P>later dislodge their plans or prejudice the post-employment <BR>

<P>opportunities of the employees most knowledgeable about the agency's <BR>

<P>functions.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>OVER-REACTION TO PROCUREMENT PROBLEMS <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Several corporatizing initiatives focus on the need to take the <BR>

<P>activity from under the Brooks Act and similar statutes.  Where <BR>

<P>inadequacies of the federal procurement process are the principal reason <BR>

<P>for undertaking the change in the nature of the entity, it is suggested <BR>

<P>that it might be easier to obtain Congressional action to waive the <BR>

<P>offending statutes rather than setting up a totally new entity.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Federal agencies do undertake timely procurements without protest.  <BR>

<P>The National Aeronautic and Space Administration's $800 million dollar <BR>

<P>&quot;SEWP&quot; procurement for seven classes of computer workstations and <BR>

<P>integration services is a case in point.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     It was recently highlighted by officials of the Congressional <BR>

<P>Research Service that &quot;procurement is only one of 15 or so activities of <BR>

<P>management...Because it involves money, and it's in the area where <BR>

<P>government and private industry interface, it has a high risk.  But <BR>

<P>still, it's only one aspect.&quot;  The remedy should fit the need.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>APPENDIX A<BR>

<P>PRIVATIZATION INITIATIVES IN THE FY 1996 BUDGET<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>     The President's FY 1996 Federal Budget includes a number of new and <BR>

<P>creative privatization initiatives.  Because of the format used, many of <BR>

<P>these initiatives are not contained in a single section of the Budget.  <BR>

<P>Therefore, the following is a resource compilation, using the titles of <BR>

<P>sections and page numbers, of the initiatives discussed with quotes or <BR>

<P>summaries for each initiative.  This summary is designed to enhance an <BR>

<P>understanding of the initiatives included in the FY 1996 Budget and to <BR>

<P>assist Federal managers as they review current approaches to existing <BR>

<P>programs.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>FROM A CITIZEN'S GUIDE TO THE FEDERAL BUDGET<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 15 - &quot;Now, the President and the Vice President are redoubling <BR>

<P>their efforts.  In what they call Phase II of reinventing Government, <BR>

<P>they are looking across Government for agencies and programs to <BR>

<P>eliminate or restructure, and activities to shift to States, localities <BR>

<P>or the private sector.&quot;  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>FROM BUDGET     <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Sharing the Benefits of Economic Growth <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 6 - The Budget Message of the President.  &quot;In the coming <BR>

<P>months, the Vice President will lead Phase II of our crusade to reinvent <BR>

<P>Government - an effort to identify other agencies and programs to <BR>

<P>restructure or terminate, to sort out responsibilities among Federal, <BR>

<P>State and local levels of government and to choose functions better <BR>

<P>performed by the private sector.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 14 - The President's Proposal for a Deduction for up to <BR>

<P>$10,000 in Post Secondary Education and Training Expenses.  &quot;This <BR>

<P>benefit will be available for tuition and fees for any college, <BR>

<P>university or vocational program eligible for Federal assistance.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 19 - Improving America's Schools Act - Technology for <BR>

<P>Education.  The new Title II Professional Development Program provides <BR>

<P>in part; &quot;a Technology Learning Challenge to create a partnership among <BR>

<P>States, schools and the private sector to raise education and training <BR>

<P>achievement by innovatively using technology.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 20 - School-to-Work Opportunities Act.  &quot;School-to-Work <BR>

<P>supports State, local and private efforts to build an education and <BR>

<P>training system that helps all youth get knowledge and skills to move <BR>
smoothly from school to career-oriented work...&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 24 - Maintaining and Enhancing the Private Sector Role.  <BR>

<P>&quot;Under the President's proposal; (1) business and labor will be key <BR>

<P>partners in designing adult and youth programs and (2) government will <BR>

<P>recognize firms that have enjoyed the most success in upgrading skills.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Building on Our Economic Record <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 39 - Savings from Government Restructuring.  &quot;We also propose <BR>

<P>additional savings below the &quot;freeze&quot; level in 1996-2000.  We will <BR>

<P>achieve many of these savings by proposing, as a part of Phase II of <BR>

<P>Reinventing Government, to terminate and restructure agencies and <BR>

<P>programs and to shift functions to the States, localities and the <BR>

<P>private sector. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 43 - Federal Investment in Infrastructure.  &quot;The President in <BR>

<P>January 1993 issued Executive Order 12893 - requiring increased use of <BR>

<P>economic analysis and promoting public private partnerships - to help <BR>

<P>ensure that our infrastructure investments are as effective as <BR>

<P>possible.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 50 - What the Federal Government Does.  &quot;In many cases, the <BR>

<P>Administration is not proposing huge sums of money to attack problems.  <BR>

<P>Rather, it seeks to use the Federal Government as a catalyst for State <BR>

<P>and local decision making, or to leverage those funds for assistance <BR>

<P>from State and local governments or the private sector.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Controlling Violent Crime and Drug Abuse<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 66 - Privatizing Federal Prisons.  &quot;The budget includes $73 <BR>

<P>million to activate six new Federal prison facilities and expand <BR>

<P>capacity at five others.  ...the Administration plans to privatize the <BR>

<P>management and operations of most future Federal facilities under <BR>

<P>construction...  The Administration will privatize three of the five <BR>

<P>minimum and low-security prisons and one detention facility scheduled to <BR>

<P>open in FY 1996.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Ensuring a Clean Environment<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 83 - Private Sector Partnerships.  &quot;The President's Climate <BR>

<P>Change Action Plan relies almost entirely on partnerships between <BR>

<P>government and the private sector.&quot;  ...the plan utilizes market <BR>

<P>incentives and fosters cooperative approaches with industry to reduce <BR>

<P>greenhouse gases without harming the economy.&quot; <BR>

<P>  <BR>

<P>     Page 90 - Enhanced Natural Resource Protection.  &quot;The <BR>

<P>Administration will seek legislation to provide the National Park <BR>

<P>Service with additional authorities to collect user fees and lease <BR>

<P>facilities.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Investing In Science and Technology<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 96 - Agency Specific Initiatives.  This section of the Budget <BR>

<P>provides a series of investments and examples of Federal resources being <BR>

<P>used in cooperation with private sector efforts to supplement private <BR>

<P>research and development (R&amp;D).  A large percent of Federal R&amp;D <BR>

<P>resources are provided to private institutions and/or are accomplished <BR>

<P>through contracts with private sector providers.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Continuing the Commitment to Health and Security<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 107 - Streamlining the Medicare Program.  &quot;The Budget includes <BR>

<P>$20.2 million for the Medicare Transaction System (MTS), which will <BR>

<P>bring together all Medicare automated claims processing functions, <BR>

<P>letting HCFA streamline contractor operations and letting beneficiaries <BR>

<P>interact more easily with the Medicare program.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>Maintaining a Quality Military Force<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 127 - Investing in Dual-Use Technology.  &quot;The Technology <BR>

<P>Reinvestment Program (TRP) awards Federal funds competitively, on a cost <BR>

<P>shared basis, to enable industry led projects to create new dual use <BR>

<P>technologies...  Since the start of the TRP program in 1993, over 15,000 <BR>

<P>companies have submitted over 3,000 proposals to participate...  The <BR>

<P>budget requests $500 million for the TRP program.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 127 - Shrinking the Defense Infrastructure.  &quot;DOD is committed <BR>

<P>to assisting the economic redevelopment of communities affected by base <BR>

<P>closures.  The President's Five Point Plan for Revitalizing Base Closure <BR>

<P>Communities speeds the transfer of base property for economic <BR>

<P>development and provides transition assistance for communities and <BR>

<P>workers.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 128 - Streamlining the Civilian Workforce.  &quot;DOD is committed <BR>

<P>to streamlining its civilian workforce to increase its efficiency and <BR>

<P>effectiveness, without sacrificing quality or compromising military <BR>

<P>readiness.  DOD projects a 22 percent reduction in civilian positions <BR>
from 1993-1999.  It has targeted headquarters, procurement, finance, and <BR>

<P>personnel staffs...&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Reinventing the Federal Government--Phase I<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 137 - Using Performance Information in the Budget Process.  <BR>

<P>&quot;OMB's budget review of the Housing and Urban Development Department <BR>

<P>(HUD) found that the quality of public housing compared unfavorably with <BR>

<P>private low-income housing and subsidized housing alternatives in terms <BR>

<P>of their physical condition, crime problems and neighborhood <BR>

<P>environment.  Partly due to such information, OMB agreed with HUD to <BR>

<P>&quot;end public housing as we know it&quot; by shifting assistance to portable <BR>

<P>vouchers by 1998.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 137 - Integrating Financial and Performance Information.  &quot;In <BR>

<P>addition, we will propose legislation to require that the full accruing <BR>

<P>cost of pensions (and other costs) be reflected in future agency budgets <BR>

<P>to help link program resources with the outputs and outcomes they <BR>

<P>generate.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 138 - Developing Streamlining Plans.  &quot;Consulting employee's <BR>

<P>unions as well, agencies worked to develop plans that focused on <BR>
delivering services critical to their missions.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Reinventing the Federal Government--Phase II<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;While preparing this Budget, the President asked his senior <BR>

<P>advisors as well as the departments and agencies for bold, creative, <BR>

<P>innovative, new ideas about how to deliver services and benefits to the <BR>

<P>American people...  In the reviews that produced the five major <BR>

<P>restructuring in this budget, the Administration organized its ideas <BR>

<P>around a few basis themes:  Consolidation, Devolution, Privatization and <BR>

<P>Termination.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 144 - HUD.  &quot;These reforms will create new performance <BR>

<P>partnerships between HUD, State and local governments, the private <BR>

<P>sector and community-based organizations...  HUD's workforce will shrink <BR>

<P>by over 4,000 as a direct result...<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 145 - HUD.  &quot;Current residents of public housing and privately <BR>

<P>owned assisted housing projects will get certificates and the freedom to <BR>

<P>use them to help pay rent in the private market.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 148 - Energy.  <BR>

<P>     o     Privatize Power Marketing Administrations, raising $3.7 <BR>
           billion.<BR>

<P>     o     Convert Bonneville Power to a Government Corporation.<BR>

<P>     o     Privatize Naval Petroleum Reserves, raising $1.6 billion.<BR>

<P>     o     Sell Excess Uranium, raising $400 million.<BR>

<P>     o     Productivity and contract reform.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Page 149 - DOT.<BR>

<P>     o     Unified grants to give States and localities more <BR>

<P>flexibility.<BR>

<P>     o     State Infrastructure Banks to leverage public and private <BR>

<P>sector investment.<BR>

<P>     o     Transfer of the Air Traffic Control System to a wholly-owned <BR>

<P>Government corporation. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 151 - GSA.  &quot;GSA will accelerate it reinvention efforts by <BR>

<P>asking of each of its service functions, &quot;Why can't the private sector <BR>

<P>provide this service or activity more effectively?...  Over the next two <BR>

<P>to three years, we estimate that GSA's FTE will fall by more that half.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 152 - OPM.  &quot;We will grant agencies the authority to perform <BR>

<P>(training and background investigations) themselves, or procure them <BR>

<P>from the private sector or from privatized OPM business units.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>Page 155 - Other Efforts.  <BR>

<P>     o     Liminating the Army Corps of Engineers Local Projects Role.<BR>

<P>     o     Reinventing the Bureau of Mines.<BR>

<P>     o     Privatizing the Helium Program.<BR>

<P>     o     Expanding Lease Authority to the National Park Service.<BR>

<P>     o     Privatizing Portions of the National Weather Service.<BR>

<P>     o     Relying on the Private Sector for NASA Communications with <BR>

<P>           Spacecraft.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Other Reforms<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 163 - Promoting Private Sector Investment in Information <BR>

<P>Technology.<BR>

<P>     o     Remove Barriers to Competition in Telecommunications.<BR>

<P>     o     Protect Intellectual Property Rights.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>FROM ANALYTIC PERSPECTIVES<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 14 - Physical Assets.  &quot;These include factories, machinery, <BR>

<P>office buildings, residential structures, land and the government's <BR>

<P>physical assets such as military hardware and highways.  Automobiles and <BR>

<P>consumer appliances are also included in this category.  The total <BR>

<P>amount of such capital is vast, amounting to around $24 trillion in <BR>

<P>1994.  By comparison, GDP was less than $7 trillion.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;The Federal Government's contribution to this stock of capital <BR>

<P>includes its own physical assets plus $0.5 trillion in accumulated <BR>

<P>grants to State and local governments for capital projects.  The Federal <BR>

<P>Government has financed about one-fifth of the physical capital held by <BR>

<P>other levels of government.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 26 - Increase the Number of Empowerment Zones.  &quot;Under the <BR>

<P>Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993, certain tax incentives were <BR>

<P>provided for nine empowerment zones and 95 enterprise communities...  <BR>

<P>The Administration proposes to provide tax incentives for two additional <BR>

<P>urban empowerment zones, increasing the total number to 11.&quot;  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 38 - Asset Sales.  &quot;The Administration plans to privatize four <BR>

<P>Power Marketing Administrations (PMAs), the Naval Petroleum Reserves <BR>

<P>(NPR), the United States Enrichment Corporation (USEC), and the Helium <BR>

<P>Fund.  In addition, it plans to sell excess uranium and a portion of the <BR>

<P>Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR).  Proceeds from the sale of USEC will <BR>

<P>be earmarked for the Nuclear Waste Disposal Fund.  SPR proceeds will be <BR>

<P>earmarked for the decommissioning of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve <BR>

<P>Weeks Island, Louisiana, site.&quot;  &quot;The five year 1996- 2000 total <BR>

<P>proceeds are estimated at $7,324 million.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 94 - Physical Investment.  &quot;Outlays for the acquisition of <BR>

<P>major equipment are estimated to be $6.4 billion in 1996.  The largest <BR>

<P>items are for the space program and the air traffic control system.  <BR>

<P>Collections for the sale of facilities are expected to exceed <BR>

<P>disbursements by $0.3 billion, largely due to the proposed sale of the <BR>

<P>United States Enrichment Corporation.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;Grants to State and local governments for physical investments are <BR>

<P>estimated to be $39.3 billion in 1996.  More than half of these outlays <BR>

<P>or $22.9 billion, are to assist States and localities with <BR>

<P>transportation infrastructure, including the proposed new unified <BR>

<P>transportation infrastructure block grant for 1996.  Other major grants <BR>

<P>for physical investment fund sewage treatment plants, community <BR>

<P>development, and public housing.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 100 - OMB Bulletin 94-08.  &quot;OMB Bulletin 94-08, Planning and <BR>

<P>Budgeting for the Acquisition of Fixed Assets was developed to provide <BR>
guidance for agencies on what fixed asset planning should include.  <BR>

<P>Agencies were requested to approach planning for fixed assets in the <BR>

<P>context of strategic plans to carry out their missions, and to consider <BR>

<P>alternative methods of meeting their goals.  Systematic analysis of the <BR>

<P>full life-cycle expected costs and benefits was required, along with <BR>

<P>risk analysis and assessment of alternative means of acquiring assets.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 100 - Funding Mechanisms.  &quot;This budget proposes to make <BR>

<P>agencies responsible for fixed assets by giving them the authority to <BR>

<P>acquire and manage such assets in the most cost effective manner <BR>

<P>available.&quot;  This proposal would transform the General Services <BR>

<P>Administration into a government-wide policy and oversight organization <BR>

<P>for administrative services, except for personnel services.&quot;  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 101 - Major Acquisition Proposals.  &quot;The 1996 budget requests <BR>

<P>$1.0 billion for GSA for the construction or acquisition of buildings.  <BR>

<P>GSA has traditionally funded the construction, as well as operations and <BR>

<P>renovations, through the Federal Buildings Fund.  However, this budget <BR>

<P>proposes a direct appropriation for the construction and acquisition of <BR>

<P>general and special purpose space to house Federal agency requirements.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>     Page 113 - Investments in National Capital.  &quot;Table 7-11 <BR>

<P>illustrates the unified budget reorganized as GAO recommends to have a <BR>

<P>separate component for investment in national capital.  The component is <BR>

<P>roughly estimated to be $120 billion in 1996.  It includes <BR>

<P>infrastructure outlays financed by Federal grants to State and local <BR>

<P>governments, such as highways and sewer projects, as well as direct <BR>

<P>Federal purchases of infrastructure, such as electric power generation <BR>

<P>equipment.&quot; <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 123 - Federal Disaster Insurance.  &quot;The Federal flood control <BR>

<P>program has been relatively successful...  In fact, given that the <BR>

<P>mapping of flood hazard zones is virtually complete, the success of the <BR>

<P>flood insurance program has raised the possibility of investigating ways <BR>

<P>to privatize non-catastrophic portions of the program.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;Also, consistent with the flood insurance program, future <BR>

<P>evaluations of the crop insurance program can explore further <BR>

<P>opportunities for increasing the private sector's share of risk for non-<BR>

<P>catastrophic coverage.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 128 - Program Privatization, Termination and Restructuring.  <BR>
With regard to the Government's role in the provision of credit, there <BR>

<P>are three proposals in this year's budget that recommend such <BR>

<P>privatization.<BR>

<P>       &quot;The Administration is considering submitting legislation which <BR>

<P>would fully privatize The College Construction Loan Insurance <BR>

<P>Association (Connie Lee) by divesting the Secretary of Education's stock <BR>

<P>ownership in the corporation and repealing the Corporation's enabling <BR>

<P>legislation.&quot;  &quot;The Administration is also considering proposing <BR>

<P>legislation to privatize the Student Loan Marketing Association (Sallie <BR>

<P>Mae).&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;The budget proposes to completely privatize the Rural Telephone <BR>

<P>Bank (RTB) at the beginning of 1996, after which it would continue its <BR>

<P>mission as a private lender.&quot;   <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Page 167 - Aid to State and Local Governments - Highlights of the <BR>

<P>Federal Aid Program.  &quot;The Administration is proposing a variety of <BR>

<P>consolidations to provide greater flexibility and increase <BR>

<P>accountability.&quot;  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;Over three years, HUD will consolidate 60 programs into three <BR>

<P>flexible, performance based funds and transform public housing into a <BR>
system that works for people and communities.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     &quot;At DOT, the proposed State Infrastructure Banks program will <BR>

<P>provide $2 billion to capitalize new State infrastructure banks.  These <BR>

<P>banks will enable jurisdictions to leverage more easily public and <BR>

<P>private resources for transportation infrastructure and encourage more <BR>

<P>business like strategies for financing the national transportation <BR>

<P>system.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>APPENDIX B<BR>

<P>&quot;GOGO TO GOCO--ON THE ROAD TO PRIVATIZATION&quot; <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>NATIONAL INSTITUTE FOR PETROLEUM AND ENERGY RESEARCH<BR>

<P>BARTLESVILLE, OKLAHOMA<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>     In October 1983, the Department of Energy (DOE) began the move to <BR>

<P>privatize its center in Bartlesville, Oklahoma.  In 1983, it was a <BR>

<P>Government-owned and Government-operated (GOGO) facility with a staff of <BR>

<P>about 160.  Today, it is a Government-owned but Contractor-operated <BR>

<P>(GOCO) facility with a staff of about 250.  Renamed as the National <BR>

<P>Institute for Petroleum and Energy Research (NIPER), the center is run <BR>

<P>by the BDM Corporation, and does an increasing volume of business with <BR>

<P>the private sector.  This is a ten-year success story along the road to <BR>

<P>privatization, and the lessons learned along the way may be useful to <BR>

<P>others.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     To establish NIPER, the DOE issued a request for proposals to not-<BR>

<P>for-profit corporations with the long term idea that the winner would <BR>

<P>bring new energy to the endeavor, that existing civil servants would <BR>

<P>move into positions with the new entity, and that over a period of <BR>

<P>several years, DOE would divest itself of the activity entirely.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The IIT Research Institute in Chicago won the initial competition, <BR>

<P>and while they brought in new business from outside of government, the <BR>

<P>volume was affected greatly by the precipitous drop in oil prices from <BR>

<P>$42 to $22 for a barrel of crude oil.  The industry was confused on how <BR>

<P>to make research and other investment decisions.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The initial contract with IITRI was for five years with an option, <BR>

<P>which was extended--DOE was not able to totally divest itself of NIPER <BR>

<P>during the initial term of the contract as planned.  In 1993, DOE made <BR>

<P>the decision to open the competition to for-profit corporations, and it <BR>

<P>was won by the BDM Corporation.  Some believe in retrospect, that the <BR>

<P>initial contract should have been open to for-profit corporations as <BR>

<P>well as not-for-profit entities for a variety of reasons, including the <BR>

<P>initial need for investment capital in undertaking such a venture.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     The parameters of the BDM contract with DOE are that the facility <BR>

<P>is operated as a Government-Owned-Contractor Operated Facility much like <BR>

<P>other DOE Management and Operations (M&amp;O) contracts.  The contract is <BR>

<P>cost plus award fee for five years at a ceiling of $211 million, <BR>

<P>excluding work for others.  A subcontractor is the University of Tulsa.  <BR>

<P>The NIPER facility covers a 17-acre campus of 16 buildings with over <BR>

<P>155,000 square feet of laboratory space with a variety of high-tech <BR>

<P>equipment including CT and NMR Scans, mass spectroscopy, and multiphase <BR>

<P>permeability apparatus.  In addition to DOE, its clients include <BR>

<P>Phillips Petroleum, Akzo Chemicals, Intratech, Design Institute for <BR>

<P>Physical Properties Measurement, America Petroleum Institute, ARCO, <BR>

<P>Shell, the Department of the Navy, the Advanced Research Program Agency, <BR>

<P>and the Defense Fuel Supply Command.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Even though the price of oil is still low, there is an increasing <BR>

<P>demand for NIPER's services by the private sector.  It seems that <BR>

<P>companies are divesting themselves of their research interests and <BR>

<P>buying the capability from NIPER.    <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>     Questions concerning DOE activities may be directed to the DOE <BR>

<P>Program Manager, Tom Wesson at (918)337-4401.  Questions concerning BDM <BR>

<P>Operations may be directed to Dr. Lowell R. Smith, President and Chief <BR>

<P>Operating Officer at (918)336-2400.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>                                        December 1994       <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
